	<article class="post-637564 post type-post status-publish hentry category-energy-by-industry-2 category-insider-trading category-legal tag-batista-eike tag-blackrock-inc tag-brazil tag-insider-trading tag-latin-america tag-ogx-petroleo-e-gas-participacoes tag-oil-petroleum-and-gasoline tag-petroleo-brasileiro-sa-petrobras tag-pimco-pacific-investment-management-company tag-rio-de-janeiro-brazil tag-sao-paulo-brazil per-batista-eike des-insider-trading des-oil-petroleum-and-gasoline org-blackrock-inc org-ogx-petroleo-e-gas-participacoes org-petroleo-brasileiro-sa-petrobras org-pimco-pacific-investment-management-company geo-brazil geo-latin-america geo-rio-de-janeiro-brazil geo-sao-paulo-brazil news_keywords-brazil news_keywords-eike-batista news_keywords-insider-trading-2 news_keywords-latin-america news_keywords-ogx-petroleo-e-gas-participacoes news_keywords-oil-and-gasoline news_keywords-pimco-pacific-investment-management-company-2 news_keywords-rio-de-janeiro news_keywords-sao-paulo-brazil-2" id="post-637564">
	<header class="postHeader">
				<div class="postKicker">
			<span class="kicker"><a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/main-topics/legal/">Legal/Regulatory</a> | <a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/other-topics/insider-trading/">Insider Trading</a></span>		</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Eike Batista&#8217;s Insider Trading Case in Brazil to Test a Much-Criticized Justice System</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Dan Horch			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-11-17T01:54:08+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">November 16, 2014 8:54 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">November 16, 2014 8:54 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/17/business/dbpix-batista2/dbpix-batista-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/17/business/dbpix-batista2/dbpix-batista-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/17/business/dbpix-batista2/dbpix-batista-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003238568" width="592" height="395" alt="Eike Batista, once one of Brazilâs richest and most flamboyant men, is scheduled to defend himself in court on Tuesday."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="395"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Eike Batista, once one of Brazilâs richest and most flamboyant men, is scheduled to defend himself in court on Tuesday.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Mario Anzuoni/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/11/16/insider-trading-case-in-brazil-to-test-a-much-criticized-justice-system/" data-title="Eike Batista&#8217;s Insider Trading Case in Brazil to Test a Much-Criticized Justice System" data-description="Many in the nation will be closely following the case of Eike Batista, once one of Brazilâs richest men, to see if the system can shed its reputation for leniency on white-collar crime.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">SÃO PAULO, Brazil â  When it comes to insider trading in the United States, government officials have built careers on successful prosecutions. Hedge funds have been shut down, and regulators have ensnared even low-level employees who traded on confidential tips.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But in Brazil, no one has ever gone to jail for insider trading.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On Tuesday, however, Eike Batista, once one of the countryâs richest and most flamboyant men, is scheduled to defend himself in court against accusations of insider trading and stock market manipulation.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Many Brazilians will be closely following the case, not only to watch Mr. Batistaâs fate, but also to see if the justice system can shake off its reputation for endless delays and for leniency toward those accused of white-collar crime.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Prosecutors accuse Mr. Batista of trading on the stock of his petroleum company, OGX, after having advance knowledge about key petroleum fieldsâ lack of economic viability.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In seeking to convict him, prosecutors may also be seeking to restore confidence in the countryâs institutions. The economy is stagnant, inflation is high, and continuing investigations into corruption in the petroleum giant <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=PBR&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Petroleo Brasileiro SA Petrobras">Petrobras</a> are reaching further into the ranks of government and leading corporations.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Anger over the judicial system is widespread, with nationwide street protests last year sometimes citing the âimpunityâ of the rich and powerful.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Batistaâs case could be a litmus test of how tough the courts can be. The prosecution is claiming that Mr. Batistaâs actions caused 1.5 billion reais (about $580 million) in damages, which he could have to repay.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For years, Mr. Batista was a symbol of Brazilâs growing economic might. He founded and listed six companies on the SÃ£o Paulo stock exchange, and for a time he was the countryâs richest man, worth over $30 billion.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Institutional investors, including the fund giants Pimco and <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=BLK&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about BlackRock Inc">BlackRock</a>, invested in his companies. The governments of former President <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/d/luiz_inacio_lula_da_silva/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva.">Luiz InÃ¡cio Lula da Silva</a> and current President <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/r/dilma_rousseff/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Dilma Rousseff.">Dilma Rousseff</a> also supported Mr. Batistaâs companies with over 6 billion reais ($2.3 billion) in subsidized loans from a state-owned bank, Bndes.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Batistaâs lavish lifestyle included mansions and yachts, and sports cars that he parked in his living room. He published an autobiography subtitled âThe Path of Brazilâs Greatest Entrepreneur.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But that image quickly unraveled as one by one, his companies went bankrupt, transferred ownership or sold key assets.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Batistaâs current legal problems began in October 2012, when he promised to inject $1 billion into the petroleum company he founded, OGX, if management requested it.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">His pledge propped up the companyâs stock for a few months, but the next May, he began to sell millions of shares.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In July the company acknowledged that key petroleum fields were economically unviable. Then in September 2013, just after he had sold millions more shares, management requested the $1 billion but Mr. Batista said that a change in the companyâs business plan had released him from his commitment.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The following month OGX defaulted on $5.8 billion in debt and filed for what became Latin Americaâs largest-ever corporate bankruptcy. The company has since been reorganized, and creditors may get some of their money back eventually, but shareholders were wiped out.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Batistaâs lead lawyer, SÃ©rgio Bermudes, did not respond to emails and phone calls requesting comment. But in documents filed with the court, the defense has argued that Mr. Batista had no inside information about the petroleum fieldsâ unviability, and that he only sold shares that he was legally obliged to, since they had been pledged as collateral on a loan that came due.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">His lawyers also note that he held on to more than 50 percent of the companyâs shares until the end and lost more than anyone else in the companyâs bankruptcy.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Amid the turmoil, Mr. Batista transferred ownership of multimillion-dollar homes in Rio de Janeiro and in a nearby beach resort to his wife and sons in what he has since said was routine <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/your-money/planning/estate-planning/index.html?inline=nyt-classifier" class="tickerized" title="More articles about estate planning.">estate planning</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">If convicted, Mr. Batista could face up to 13 years in jail. But the countryâs record of prosecutions makes that outcome seem unlikely.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIn Brazil, if you can afford good lawyers, you can keep appealing forever, often on technicalities that serve no purpose other than to delay decisions,â said Claudio Weber Abramo, executive director of TransparÃªncia Brasil, an anti-corruption group.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Batistaâs defense team on Thursday filed a motion arguing that the Rio de Janeiro federal court should not have jurisdiction and requesting that the hearing be postponed. The appeals court has not yet responded, so for now Mr. Batistaâs trial is still set to start Tuesday.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Even after a court issues a judgment, Brazilian law suspends the sentence while it is under appeal, and most cases can be appealed up to the Supreme Court, which has a lengthy backlog. As a result, even defendants who are convicted can often avoid serving their sentences until the statute of limitations releases them from judgment.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But Mr. Batistaâs case is coming in a harsher environment. The involvement of multiple prosecutorsâ offices, as well as advocacy groups representing creditors and small investors, are novelties in financial crimes investigations in Brazil.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Even if Mr. Batista is convicted, the case may not indicate a broader shift in the justice system.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIf this were not a person with Mr. Batistaâs exposure in the media, itâs possible that there wouldnât have been a criminal case at all, just a civil one,â said Gilberto Braga, a finance professor at the Ibmec-Rio business school. âIn white collar crime,â he added, âthe prison sentence is hardly ever for more than a few years, and that can be converted into community service.â</p>
			<div class="nyt-article-promo">
								<div class="w190">
					<a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/09/14/fallen-brazilian-mogul-accused-of-insider-trading/?ref=dealbook"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/16/business/batista/batista-thumbWide.jpg" width="190" height="126" alt="Fallen Brazilian Mogul Eike Batista Accused of Insider Trading" /></a>
				</div>
