				<p class="nyt-article-byline">By DAN HORCH</p>
				<p class="nyt-article-summary">Eike Batista was accused of manipulating the share price of his now-bankrupt petroleum company OGX.</p>
			</div>
			
			<div class="nyt-article-promo">
								<div class="w190">
					<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/06/24/business/global/brazil-fortune-and-fate-turn-on-billionaire.html?ref=dealbook"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/06/24/business/jp-batista1/jp-batista1-thumbWide-v2.jpg" width="190" height="126" alt="Brazil, Fortune and Fate Turn on Billionaire" /></a>
				</div>
                				<h4><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/06/24/business/global/brazil-fortune-and-fate-turn-on-billionaire.html?ref=dealbook">Brazil, Fortune and Fate Turn on Billionaire</a></h4>
				<p class="nyt-article-byline">By PETER LATTMAN and SIMON ROMERO</p>
				<p class="nyt-article-summary">Once worth $34.5 billion, Eike Batistaâs holdings are now estimated at $4.8 billion and falling. With Brazilâs streets churning in protest, the markets â and Mr. Batistaâs fortune â are on uncertain terrain.</p>
			</div>
			
